1 Background

Datasets

This analysis draws on three studies that characterise the 29,903bp RNA genome of SARS-CoV-2 for structural features (Andrews et al. 2020; Rangan, Zheludev, and Das 2020), sequence conservation (Rangan, Zheludev, and Das 2020) and RNA modifications (Kim et al. 2020). We use these data to prioitize ~9500 candidate siRNAs generated by the OligoWalk pipeline (Mathews 2010), DSIR (Vert et al. 2006; Filhol 2012) and 36 candidate siRNAs designed by Tristan Scott. In addition, 163 experimentally validated SARS-CoV-1 siRNAs are assessed for homology with SARS-CoV-2.

Genome browser

For Visualisation outside this report, visit the UCSC SARS-CoV-2 Genome Browser (Fernandes et al. 2020). Data from this analysis can be visualised on more than 20 additional tracks served from a custom trackHub.

Approach

OligoWalk uses a machine learning algorithm to assess the effect of target and guide-strand self-structures and 24 sequence features known to impact siRNA efficacy in shorlisting candidates. DSIR uses a simple linear model that considers only sequence features of candidates. Both OligoWalk and DSIR assess the entire SARS2 genome in sliding 21 bp windows for candidate siRNAs, so in regions of the genome where structural or sequence features are suboptimal, no candidates are reported. For each algorithm, we produce a list of the top 10 candidates and the bottom 10 candidates, as ranked by efficacy.

For the combined analysis, we restrict the candidates to those that fall in windows defined by the lack of secondary structure (viz. Rangan, Andrews), sequence conservation (in GISAID, in SARS-CoV-1, in bat coronaviruses and in vertebrate coronaviruses), off-target effects (seed sequence frequency in human transcripts) and finally consider endogenous mRNA modifications of viral genes.

Excel sheets and figures from this report can be found in the results folder.

2.1 OligoWalk Candidates

SARS2.OW <- SARS2.data[!is.na(SARS2.data$OW.prob), grepl("chr|start|end|strand|name|refSeq|OW", names(SARS2.data)) ]

OligoWalk considers the equilibrium of the siRNA guide strand hybridization with the target mRNA. The software calculates thermodynamic features of sense-antisense hybridization and predicts the free energy changes of oligonucleotides binding to a target RNA. The SVM uses this information in addition to sequence-based features to propose efficient siRNAs targeting a given mRNA sequence. Analysis of SARS-CoV-2 gRNA resulted in 8530 candidates.

  • Matthews 2010

2.2 DSIR Candidates

SARS2.DSIR <- SARS2.data[!is.na(SARS2.data$DSIR.score), grepl("chr|start|end|strand|name|refSeq|DSIR", names(SARS2.data)) ]

DSIR implements a simple linear model combining basic sequence features of siRNAs for efficacy prediction. The model enables quantification of the effect of nucleotides at particular positions and of sequence motifs. Analysis of SARS-CoV-2 gRNA resulted in 1646 candidates.

  • Filhol et al 2012
  • Vert et al 2016

2.4 VIRsiRNAdb candidates shared with SARS1

VIRsiRNAdb is a curated database of experimentally validated viral siRNA/shRNA targeting diverse genes of 42 important human viruses including influenza, SARS and Hepatitis viruses.

In total, VIRsiRNAdb reports 163 published and validated siRNAs from SARS-CoV-1, and 61 have a ‘hit’ in SARS-CoV-2 with no more than 2 mismatches.

2.4.1 Top and bottom 10

Top and bottom 10 candidates, ranked by experimental efficacy (Efficacy). The top 10 scores are indicated in green, the bottom 10 in red.

SARS2.VIRsiDB <- SARS2.data[!is.na(SARS2.data$VIRsiRNAid), grepl("chr|start|end|strand|refSeq|VIRsiRNAid|Target_Region|Cell_Line|Test_Object|Efficacy|PMID|OW.prob|DSIR.score|COH.name", names(SARS2.data)) ]

SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy <- gsub("Low",33,SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy)
SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy <- gsub("Medium",55,SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy)
SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy <- gsub("High",99,SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy)
SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy <- as.numeric(SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy)

SARS2.VIRsiDB <- SARS2.VIRsiDB[order(SARS2.VIRsiDB$Efficacy, decreasing = TRUE),]

SARS2.VIRsiDB.top10 <- head(n=10,SARS2.VIRsiDB[ , !grepl("SARS1|OW.end_diff|COH.name", names(SARS2.VIRsiDB)) ])
SARS2.VIRsiDB.top10$selection <- "TOP_10"
SARS2.VIRsiDB.top10.gr <- makeGRangesFromDataFrame(SARS2.VIRsiDB.top10, keep.extra.columns=TRUE)

SARS2.VIRsiDB.bottom10 <- tail(n=10,SARS2.VIRsiDB[ , !grepl("SARS1|OW.end_diff|COH.name", names(SARS2.VIRsiDB)) ])
SARS2.VIRsiDB.bottom10$selection <- "BOTTOM_10"

2.4.2 Distribution of VIRsiDB efficacy scores

VIRsiDB reports Efficacy for some siRNAs as low, medium or high, and gives a numeric value between 1 and 100 for others. To combine these for ranking, as no siRNA had an Efficacy of 33, 55 or 99, such values were substituted with low, medium and high Efficacy, respectively.

3 Filters

To narrow the list of 9442 candidates, we filter based on various criteria including sequence conservation, secondary structure, putative off-target effects and viral RNA modifications.

3.2 Structure

RNA secondary structure is thought to play an important role in siRNA efficacy. Several methods exist to assess the stability of mRNA secondary structures and the duplexes they form with cognate siRNAs. Thermodynamically unstable regions are consistent with the absence of defined structures that might preclude siRNA access, and so are preferred target sites.

3.2.1 Rangan et al 2020

Rangan R, Zheludev IN, Hagey RJ, et al. RNA genome conservation and secondary structure in SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-related viruses: a first look. RNA. 2020;26(8):937-959. doi:10.1261/rna.076141.120

# number and length of intervals

rangan_numIntervals <- length(rangan.Table3.cons_unstr.gr)
# number of siRNAs within intervals
rangan_SARS2.gr     <- subsetByOverlaps(SARS2.gr,rangan.Table3.cons_unstr.gr)
rangan_filtered     <- nrow(values(rangan_SARS2.gr))

dtrack_all <- AnnotationTrack(rangan.Table3.cons_unstr.gr,

In Supplementary Dataset 1, Andrews et al present ScanFold results for 524 regions that are likely highly-structured, where stretches of at least one base pair with an average Z-score < -1 were extracted and refolded. To infer unstructured regions, we take the inverse (A) of the structured intervals, totalling 478 ranges covering 10649 base pairs. The unstructured regions include 6226 siRNAs, or 65.94% of all candidates (bottom track).

3.3 Off-targets

Unintended off-target silencing is common in siRNA experiments, particularly via “microRNA-like” effects where siRNA-induced sequence-dependent regulation of transcripts occurs through partial sequence complementarity to 3′ UTRs of off-target transcripts, producing false-positives (Jackson et al. 2006; Jackson and Linsley 2010). To avoid such effects, we counted the frequency of “seed sequences” (base pairs 2-8 at the 5′ end of candidate siRNAs) in the human transcriptome (Gencode v34, released 11.2019 Transcript sequences), and ranked candidate siRNAs accordingly.

dtrack_all <- DataTrack(SARS2.gr,

3.4 Modified sites

Kim D, Lee JY, Yang JS, Kim JW, Kim VN, Chang H. The Architecture of SARS-CoV-2 Transcriptome. Cell. 2020;181(4):914-921.e10. doi:10.1016/j.cell.2020.04.011

#- join the two Kim granges
kim.mod_motif.gr<- GenomicRanges::reduce(import.bed("beds/kim.mod_motif.bed", genome = "wuhCor1"))
kim.mod_sites.gr<- GenomicRanges::reduce(import.bed("beds/kim.mod_sites.bed", genome = "wuhCor1"))
#- join into one grange
kim.mod.gr<- c(kim.mod_sites.gr, kim.mod_motif.gr)
#- find overlapping siRNAs  
kim.mod.SARS2 <- subsetByOverlaps(SARS2.gr, kim.mod.gr)

kim_filtered    <- nrow(values(kim.mod.SARS2))


motifs_track_all  <- AnnotationTrack(kim.mod_motif.gr, strand = "*", 
                           name = "motifs",fill="gray",col="transparent",
                           showOverplotting=FALSE)

sites_track_all  <- AnnotationTrack(kim.mod_sites.gr, strand = "*", 
                           name = "sites",fill="blue",col="transparent",
                           showOverplotting=FALSE)
atrack_both <- OverlayTrack(trackList=list(motifs_track_all,sites_track_all))

plotTracks(list(SARS2_gtrack, SARS2_annoTrack, atrack_both, SARS2_gtrack), margin = 20)

Kim et al 2020 produced a high-resolution map of the SARS-CoV-2 transcriptome and epitranscriptome using NanoPore sequencing. They report 41 potential modification sites (shown in blue) and that the most frequently observed motif harbouring madifications is AAGAA (77 sites, shown in grey). Modification of sites at an “AAGAA-like” motif are found throughout the viral genome and enriched in genomic positions 28,500–29,500. Long viral transcripts (gRNA, S, 3a, E, and M) are modified more often than shorter mRNAs (6, 7a, 7b, 8, and N) suggesting a transcript-specific modification mechanism. This observation hints at a functional role for modified sites, and so provides potential siRNA targets - 770 candidates (8.16%) overlap with modified sites or an AAGAA motif.

4 Selected siRNAs

To select a final list of candidates, we take the full list of 9442 candidates and keep those that that are, in order:

  • In structurally accessable regions of the SARS-CoV-2 genome (viz. Rangan et al, 688; Andrews et al , 6226)
  • In the 90th percentile with respect to frequency in sequenced (GISAID) SARS-CoV-2 genomes (949)
  • Common to both SARS-CoV-1 and SARS-CoV-2 (437)
  • In the 90th percentile with respect to sequence conservation in bat betacoronavirusus (MULTIZ44; 1606) and vertebrate coronaviruses (MULTIZ119; 3127)
  • In the 10th percentile with respect to seed sequence frequency in the human transcriptome (945)
  • Likely to cover a modified base (770)
